<chapter xml:id="chapter-periodic" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Trigonometric functions</title>

<section xml:id="section-periodic-behaviour">
<title>Periodic behaviour</title>

<example xml:id="example-periodic-spring">
	<title>Oscillation of a mass on a spring</title>

	<p>
	Consider a spring with a mass attached to one end and the other end attached to a wall.
	For simplicity,
	we will assume that the mass rests on a frictionless surface.
	Let <m>s(t)</m> represent the position of the spring relative to the wall at time <m>t</m>,
	and let <m>\rmsubscript{s}{eq}</m> represent the <q>equilibrium</q> position.
	</p>

	<figure>
		<caption>A mass attached to a spring.</caption>

		<sbsgroup width="80%">

			<sidebyside><figure>
				<caption>
					At the equilibrium position,
					where the spring is neither compressed nor stretched.
				</caption>
				<image>
					<description>A mass attached to a spring, at equilibrium position.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/mass-equil.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>

			<sidebyside><figure>
				<caption>
					At a negative position,
					where the spring is compressed.
				</caption>
				<image>
					<description>A mass attached to a spring, at a negative position with the spring compressed.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/mass-compressed.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>

			<sidebyside><figure>
				<caption>
					At a positive position,
					where the spring is stretched.
				</caption>
				<image>
					<description>A mass attached to a spring, at a positive position with the spring stretched.</description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/mass-stretched.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure></sidebyside>

		</sbsgroup>

	</figure>

	<p>
	Imagine what will happen if the mass is held at a position that compresses the spring,
	and then is released.
	The initial velocity of the mass is <m>0</m>,
	as it is starting from rest,
	but the force of the spring causes it to accelerate.
	The mass reaches its highest velocity as it passes the equilibrium position,
	since past that point the spring is now stretched and begins to pull back on the mass.
	The force of the stretched spring now causes the spring to slow down,
	stop,
	and begin to move back towards the wall.
	We now consider the mass to have negative velocity as it is moving in the opposite direction,
	and its distance from the wall is now decreasing.
	The mass reaches its largest negative velocity as it again passes the equilibrium position
	before slowing down, stopping,
	and repeating the motion all over again.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-velocity-spring-mass">
		<caption> A velocity graph for a mass attached to a spring. </caption>
		<image width="50%">
			<description> A velocity graph for a mass attached to a spring. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/sine-for-spring.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	Now consider the position function <m>s(t)</m>.
	For simplicity,
	let's label the equilibrium position as <m>s = 0</m>,
	so that positions closer to the wall than equilibrium and negative,
	and positions farther from the wall are positive.
	If the mass begins at position <m>s(0) = -A</m>
	(with <m>A</m> positive),
	it will reach the equilibrium position <m>s(t) = 0</m> at the same time that the velocity is at its peak,
	and will by symmetry will the position <m>s(t) = A</m> will be the furthest from the wall it reaches,
	at the same time that velocity is a gain <m>0</m>.
	Then its position will return back to <m>s(t) = -A</m> following the same pattern in reverse.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-position-spring-mass">
		<caption> A position graph for a mass attached to a spring. </caption>
		<image width="50%">
			<description> A position graph for a mass attached to a spring. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/cos-for-spring.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
The repetitive motion in <xref ref="example-periodic-spring" /> is called <term>periodic</term>.
The <term>period</term> is the time duration required to complete one cycle of the repetition.
The smoothly oscillating functions in <xref ref="figure-periodic-position-spring-mass" />
are called <term>sinusoidal functions</term>.
<!-- There are two basic sinusoidal functions:
the sine and cosine functions. -->
</p>

<!-- TODO sidebyside figures of sin and cos -->

<!-- TODO amplitude, frequency, period, bias, phase shift -->

</section>

<section>
<title>Radian measure</title>

<p>
A circle with radius <m>R = 1</m> has circumference <m>C = 2 \pi</m>.
This means that if we cut the circle and <q>unrolled</q> it into a straight line segment,
its length would be <m>2 \pi</m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-full-circumference">
	<caption> An unrolled circle of radius <m>1</m>. </caption>
	<image width="75%">
		<description> An unrolled unit circle. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/circumference.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
Given two points on the circle, we may ask the question:
<q>What is the distance along the circle between these two points?</q>
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-partial-circumference">
	<caption> A straightened arc of a unit circle. </caption>
	<image width="75%">
		<description> A straightened arc of a unit circle. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/arc.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p> Such a distance along a circle is called an <term>arc length</term>. </p>

<p>
If we draw line segments from the centre of the circle to each of two points on the circle,
an angle is created.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>Radian measure of an angle</title>

	<p>
	Given an angle formed by two line segments that meet at a vertex,
	extend the segments in the direction away from the vertex until each has length at least <m>1</m> unit,
	if necessary.
	Then the circle of radius <m>R = 1</m> centred at the vertex will cut the two segments.
	Define the <term>radian measure</term> of this angle to be the arc length between the points where the circle cuts the segments.
	</p>

</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-radian">
	<caption> Radian measure of an angle equals arc length along a unit circle. </caption>
	<image width="50%">
		<description> Radian measure of an angle equals arc length along a unit circle. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/radian.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
For example,
a right angle creates an arc that is one quarter of a circle,
and so has radian measure <me> \frac{2 \pi}{4} = \frac{\pi}{2} </me>.
A <m>45 \degree</m> angle will create an arc half the length of that for a right angle,
and so has radian measure <m>\pi / 4</m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-radian-two-examples">
	<caption> Two example radian measures. </caption>

	<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">

		<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-radian-two-examples-right">
			<caption> Radian measure of a right angle. </caption>
			<image>
				<description> Radian measure of a right angle. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/radian-right.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-radian-two-examples-45">
			<caption> Radian measure of a <m>45 \degree</m> angle. </caption>
			<image>
				<description> Radian measure of a 45-degree angle. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/radian-45.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<p>
Here are some common radian measures,
with the corresponding angle measure in degrees.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-table-radian-measure">
	<caption>Some common radian measures.</caption>
	<tabular halign="center">
		<col right="minor" /><col />
		<row bottom="minor"> <cell>Degrees</cell> <cell>Radians</cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>0 \degree</m></cell> <cell>0</cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>30 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{6}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>45 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>60 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>90 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>120 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{2 \pi}{3}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>135 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{3 \pi}{4}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>150 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{5 \pi}{6}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>180 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\pi</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>270 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>\frac{3 \pi}{2}</m></cell> </row>
		<row> <cell><m>360 \degree</m></cell> <cell><m>2 \pi</m></cell> </row>
	</tabular>
</figure>

<p>
In general, we can convert between degrees and radians by the relation
<me> 1 \degree = \frac{2 \pi}{360} \text{ radians} </me>.
</p>

<p>
Finally,
by allowing both positive- and negative-measure angles,
we can take direction into account.
To do this,
we label one of the two points on the circle as <q>first</q> and the other as <q>second</q>.
Then an angle that opens <em>counter-clockwise</em> from first point to second point is considered positive,
while an angle that opens <em>clockwise</em> from first point to second point is considered negative.
</p>

<!-- TODO figure ? -->

<p>
When working with the unit circle centred at the origin in the Cartesian plane,
we generally take the point <m>(1,0)</m> as the <q>first</q> point to act as a reference point.
</p>

<!-- TODO figure ? -->

</section>

<section>
<title>The six trigonometric functions</title>

<p>
The most basic form of periodic behaviour is to repeatedly traverse a circle,
so that every period is one traversal of the circle.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-traverse-circle">
	<caption> Traversing the unit circle. </caption>
	<image width="50%">
		<description> Traversing the unit circle. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/traverse-circle.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
Consider how the <m>x</m>-coordinate varies as we traverse the unit circle,
starting at the point <m>(1,0)</m> on the <m>x</m>-axis and moving counter-clockwise.
In particular,
let's match <m>x</m>-coordinates of positions along the circle to angles,
with variable <m>t</m> representing the angle between the radius to the reference point <m>(1,0)</m> and the radius to the position point,
as in <xref ref="figure-periodic-traverse-circle" />.
Starting at the reference point <m>(1,0)</m> on the positive <m>x</m>-axis,
we observe the following.
<ul>

	<li>
		The <m>x</m>-coordinate decreases from <m>x = 1</m> at <m>t = 0</m> to <m>x = 0</m> at the point <m>(0,1)</m> on the positive <m>y</m>-axis,
		where <m>t = \pi/2</m>.
	</li>

	<li>
		From there,
		the <m>x</m>-coordinate continues to decrease to <m>x = -1</m> when it reaches the point <m>(-1,0)</m> on the negative <m>x</m>-axis,
		where <m>t = \pi</m>.
	</li>

	<li>
		From there,
		the <m>x</m>-coordinate increases through <m>x = 0</m> at the point <m>(0,-1)</m> on the negative <m>y</m>-axis
		(where <m>t = 3\pi / 2</m>)
		back to <m>x = 1</m> when it returns to the reference point <m>(1,0)</m>.
		Even though this is at <m>t = 0</m>,
		we consider it to be <m>t = 2 \pi</m>,
		since we have now made one full traversal of the circumference of the circle.
	</li>

</ul>
Traversing the circle a second (or third, or fourth) time just repeats this behaviour.
And if we traverse the circle in reverse
(so that now <m>t</m> is considered negative),
we observe the above behaviour in reverse.
Here is the graph of <em>angle-versus-<m>x</m>-coordinate</em> formed by this behaviour.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-cos-graph">
	<caption>
		Graph of the cosine function,
		which tracks the <m>x</m>-coordinate of positions on the unit circle.
	</caption>
	<image width="100%">
		<description> Graph of the cosine function. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/cos.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<definition>
	<title>The cosine function</title>
	<p>
	Given input value <m>t</m>,
	the output value <m>\cos(t)</m> is taken to be the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the point <m>(x,y)</m> on the unit circle that forms an angle of <m>t</m> with the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
	</p>
</definition>

<p>
Also consider how the <m>y</m>-coordinate varies as we traverse the unit circle,
and how that variation tracks the variation in the angle <m>t</m>.
With an analysis similar to the one above for the variation in the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the position,
we arrive at the following graph of <em>angle-versus-<m>y</m>-coordinate</em>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-sin-graph">
	<caption>
		Graph of the cosine function,
		which tracks the <m>x</m>-coordinate of positions on the unit circle.
	</caption>
	<image width="100%">
		<description> Graph of the sine function. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/sin.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>


<definition>
	<title>The sine function</title>
	<p>
	Given input value <m>t</m>,
	the output value <m>\sin(t)</m> is taken to be the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the point <m>(x,y)</m> on the unit circle that forms an angle of <m>t</m> with the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
	</p>
</definition>

<p>
Due to the abundance of symmetry in a circle,
the graphs of the sine and cosine also display many instances of symmetry,
which we can express as transformations of functions.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-periodic-sin-cos-identities">
	<title>Identities involving sine and cosine</title>
	<p>
	The sine and cosine functions satisfy the following identities.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\sin(-t) \amp = - \sin(t)
			\amp
			\cos(-t) \amp = \cos(t)
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\sin(t - \pi/2) \amp = - \cos(t)
			\amp
			\cos(t - \pi/2) \amp = \sin(t)
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\sin(t + \pi/2) \amp = \cos(t)
			\amp
			\cos(t + \pi/2) \amp = - \sin(t)
		</mrow>
	</md>
	<me> {\bbrac{\cos(t)}}^2 + {\bbrac{\sin(t)}}^2 = 1 </me>
	</p>
</identity>


<p>
In <xref ref="section-periodic-trig-triangles" />
we will review the connection between trigonometry and the geometry of right triangles;
specifically, ratios of sides in a right triangle.
With that goal in mind,
we make the following definitions of four more trigonometric functions as ratios.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-periodic-tan-cot-sec-csc">
	<title>The tangent function and reciprocal trigonometric functions</title>
	<p>
	Given input value <m>t</m>,
	let <m>(x,y)</m> represent the point on the unit circle that forms an angle of <m>t</m> with the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
	Then we define the <term>tangent</term>, <term>cotangent</term>, <term>secant</term>, and <term>cosecant</term> functions by
	<md>
		<mrow> \tan t \amp = \frac{y}{x} \amp \sec t \amp = \frac{1}{x} </mrow>
		<mrow> \cot t \amp = \frac{x}{y} \amp \csc t \amp = \frac{1}{y} </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>
</definition>

<!-- TODO graphs of these new trig functions -->

<identity>
	<title>Rational/reciprocal relationships between trigonometric functions</title>

	<statement><p>
		We have
		<md>
			<mrow>
				\tan t \amp = \frac{\sin t}{\cos t}
				\amp
				\sec t \amp = \frac{1}{\cos t}
			</mrow>
			<mrow>
				\cot t \amp = \frac{1}{\tan t} = \frac{\cos t}{\sin t}
				\amp
				\csc t \amp = \frac{1}{\sin t}
			</mrow>
		</md>
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		With angle <m>t</m> and point <m>(x,y)</m> on the unit circle as in <xref ref="definition-periodic-tan-cot-sec-csc" />,
		we have
		<md>
			<mrow>
				\cos t \amp = x
				\amp
				\tan t \amp = \frac{y}{x}
				\amp
				\sec t \amp = \frac{1}{x}
			</mrow>
			<mrow>
				\sin t \amp = y
				\amp
				\cot t \amp = \frac{x}{y}
				\amp
				\csc t \amp = \frac{1}{y}
			</mrow>
		</md>,
		and the relationships in the pattern statement follow immediately.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-periodic-trig-triangles">
<title>Trigonometry in triangles</title>

<p>
Given a right triangle,
we can draw a unit circle centred at the vertex opposite the hypotenuse.
This circle will either cut the hypotenuse or we may extend the hypotenuse until it reaches the circle.
Treating one of the triangle's legs as representing the positive <m>x</m>-axis,
we may use the angle formed by the hypotenuse and that leg as the input to the trigonometric functions.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-periodic-cut-extend-right-triangle">
	<caption>Creating a similar right triangle in a unit circle.</caption>

	<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">

		<figure>
			<caption> Cutting a right triangle with a unit circle. </caption>
			<image>
				<description> Cutting a right triangle with a unit circle. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/cut-right-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure>
			<caption> Extending a right triangle within a unit circle. </caption>
			<image>
				<description> Extending a right triangle within a unit circle. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/cut-right-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<p>
In both cases demonstrated in <xref ref="figure-periodic-cut-extend-right-triangle" />,
the two triangles are <term>similar triangles</term>,
which means that a ratio of side lengths in one of the triangles will equal the ratio of corresponding side lengths in the other triangle.
Therefore,
<md>
	<mrow>
		\cos \theta \amp = \frac{x}{1} = \frac{a}{c}
		\amp
		\sin \theta \amp = \frac{y}{1} = \frac{b}{c}
		\amp
		\tan \theta \amp = \frac{y}{x} = \frac{b}{a}
	</mrow>
</md>,
leading to the familiar acronyms SOH CAH TOA:
<md>
	<mrow>
		\cos \theta \amp = \frac{\mathrm{adj}}{\mathrm{hyp}}
		\amp
		\sin \theta \amp = \frac{\mathrm{opp}}{\mathrm{hyp}}
		\amp
		\tan \theta \amp = \frac{\mathrm{opp}}{\mathrm{adj}}
	</mrow>
</md>.
</p>

<figure>
	<caption>SOH CAH TOA.</caption>
	<image width="33%">
		<description>SOH CAH TOA.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="periodic.d/soh-cah-toa.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-periodic-trig-accumulation">
<title>Trigonometric rate functions</title>

<p>
<xref ref="example-periodic-spring" /> has already provided us with an example of a rate/position function pair involving trigonometric functions.
Suppose we take the motion in that example to have an amplitude of <m>1</m>,
so that when the object is stopped at maximum compression of the spring and at maximum stretch of the spring,
it is <m>1</m> unit away from the central equilibrium position.
And suppose we assume that the time units are normalized so that one full period of the motion,
from compressed spring to stretched back to compressed,
represents the time domain <m>0 \le t \le 2 \pi</m>.
Then the velocity can be modelled by the sine function and the position can be modelled by the negative of the cosine function:
<md><mrow> v(t) \amp = \sin t \amp s(t) = - \cos t </mrow></md>.
The reason that we have the <em>negative</em> of the cosine function as the position function is because we took the central equilibrium position to be <m>s = 0</m>,
with <m>s \lt 0</m> representing a position closer to the wall and <m>s \gt 0</m> representing a position further from the wall compared to the centre position.
So when the object is released from a stop at a compressed position,
we are taking <m>s(0) = -1</m>.
And from the there the object moves forward,
so that the position values increase and the velocity values becomes positive.
</p>

<p>
As the object begins to move,
it accumulates displacement from the initial position <m>s(0) = -1</m>:
<md>
	<mrow> s(t) \amp = s(0) + \ccmint{0}{t}{v(u)}{u} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = -1 + \ccmint{0}{t}{\sin(u)}{u} </mrow>
</md>.
On the other hand,
we have already modelled position as <m>s(t) = - \cos(t)</m>:
<me> - \cos(t) = -1 + \ccmint{0}{t}{\sin(u)}{u} </me>.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-periodic-int-sin">
	<title>Accumulation when rate function is sine</title>
	<p>
	For all values of <m>t</m>,
	<me> \ccmint{0}{t}{\sin(u)}{u} = 1 - \cos(t) </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<p>
For a cosine rate function,
we can use the fact that cosine is just a horizontal shift of the sine function:
<me> \cos(t) = \sin(t + \pi/2) </me>.
(See <xref ref="pattern-periodic-sin-cos-identities" />.)
Accordingly, if we shift time so that we consider the velocity of the object in <xref ref="example-periodic-spring" /> as being modelled by <m>v(t) = \cos(t)</m>,
then we can just shift our position function by the same amount:
<md>
	<mrow>
		v(t) \amp = \cos(t)
		\amp
		s(t) \amp = -\cos(t + \pi/2)
	</mrow>
	<mrow>
		\amp = \sin(t + \pi/2)
		\amp
		\amp = - \bbrac{-\sin(t)}
	</mrow>
	<mrow>
		\amp \amp \amp = \sin(t)
	</mrow>
</md>.
Essentially,
we have shifted time so that <m>t = 0</m> means the moment that the object first moves through the equilibrium position at <m>s = 0</m> with its maximum positive velocity.
Again,
we think of the object as accumulating displacement from its initial position:
<md>
	<mrow> s(t) \amp = s(0) + \ccmint{0}{t}{v(u)}{u} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = 0 + \ccmint{0}{t}{\cos(u)}{u} </mrow>
</md>.
As we have decided that position in this shifted scenario should be modelled as <m>s(t) = \sin(t)</m>,
we have
<me> \sin(t) = 0 + \ccmint{0}{t}{\cos(u)}{u} </me>.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-periodic-int-cos">
	<title>Accumulation when rate function is cosine</title>
	<p>
	For all values of <m>t</m>,
	<me> \ccmint{0}{t}{\cos(u)}{u} = \sin(t) </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<example>
	<title>Computing an accumulation for a rate function involving sine and cosine</title>

	<p>
	Suppose we would like to compute <me> \ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{ 3 \sin(t) + 5 \cos(t) }{t} </me>.
	As usual, we use <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" /> to split into separate integrals and factor out the constant multiples:
	<me>
		\ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{ 3 \sin(t) + 5 \cos(t) }{t}
		= 3 \ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\sin(t)}{t}
		+ 5 \ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\cos(t)}{t}
	</me>.
	Let's continue by computing these two integrals separately.
	As we've done before in other examples,
	we use
	<xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-split" />
	of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />
	to manipulate the bounds of integration so that we can use our formulas from
	<xref ref="pattern-periodic-int-sin" /> and <xref ref="pattern-periodic-int-cos" />,
	which both involve a lower bound of <m>0</m>.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\amp \ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\sin(t)}{t}
			\amp
			\amp \ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\cos(t)}{t}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \qquad
			= \ccmint{0}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\sin(t)}{t}
			- \ccmint{0}{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\sin(t)}{t}
			\amp
			\amp \qquad
			= \ccmint{0}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\cos(t)}{t}
			- \ccmint{0}{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\cos(t)}{t}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \qquad = \bbrac{1 - \cos(3 \pi / 2)} - \bbrac{1 - \cos(\pi/2)}
			\amp
			\amp \qquad = \sin(3 \pi / 2) - \sin (\pi / 2)
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \qquad = (1 - 0) - (1 - 0)
			\amp
			\amp \qquad = -1 - 1
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \qquad = 0
			\amp
			\amp \qquad = -2
		</mrow>
	</md>
	We should have expected that the integral on the left would evaluate to <m>0</m>,
	by the symmetry of the rate function <m>\sin(t)</m> <mdash />
	the positively-oriented area over the domain <m>\pi / 2 \le t \le \pi</m>
	is the same magnitude as the negatively-oriented area over the domain <m>\pi \le t \le 3 \pi / 2</m>,
	and so cancel out when combined over the domain <m>\pi / 2 \le t \le 3 \pi / 2</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Finally, we combine the two results above to compute the original integral.
	<md>

		<mrow>
			\ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{ 3 \sin(t) + 5 \cos(t) }{t}
			\amp = 3 \ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\sin(t)}{t}
			+ 5 \ccmint{\frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{3 \pi}{2}}{\cos(t)}{t}
		</mrow>

		<mrow> \amp = 3 \cdot 0 + 5 \cdot (-2) </mrow>

		<mrow> \amp = -10 </mrow>

	</md>
	</p>
</example>

<p>
We will learn how to determine accumulation for a rate function modelled by the tangent function
in <xref ref="chapter-chain" />.
<!-- in a later chapter. -->
</p>

</section>

